    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/atac-seq-clustering-performance-interpretation/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The chromVAR package is freely available under the MIT license at www.github.com/GreenleafLab/chromVAR and as Supplementary Software. The motifmatchr R package is freely available under a GPL-3 license is available at www.github.com/GreenleafLab/motifmatchr and as supplementary software.",
      "asbval:note": "chromVAR is an R package; R is the environment. Paper uses R packages (Rtsne, hierarchical clustering) for analysis and visualization.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4401",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "atac-seq-clustering-performance-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "R: Environment for extracting, tabulating, and calculating summary statistics on benchmark metrics",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:39:11.714340+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/atac-seq-clustering-performance-interpretation/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In contrast, chromVAR analysis is highly robust to low sequencing depth and readily scales to hundreds or thousands of cells or samples. Budget-constrained researchers often face a trade-off between the number of samples to sequence and the sequencing depth for each sample; sparse sequencing analysis coupled with chromVAR analysis may enable new applications of 'bulk' ATAC, DNase-seq or other epigenomic methods as large-scale screening tools.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper positions chromVAR as a robust method for clustering and analysis, but does not frame the paper as a comprehensive benchmark study comparing multiple published methods. The paper is primarily a methods paper introducing chromVAR, not a benchmark comparison paper.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4401",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "atac-seq-clustering-performance-interpretation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you need to assess whether a given ATAC-seq clustering method (or variant) is competitive on your data or when evaluating which published method to adopt.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:39:11.714340+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/background-peak-selection-normalization/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To account for these technical confounders, \"background\" peak sets are created for each annotation, which comprise of an equal number of peaks matched for GC content and average accessibility (Supplementary Figs. 2\u20135; Supplementary Note 2). The raw accessibility deviations for these background peak sets are used to compute a bias corrected deviation and z-score for each annotation and cell, providing a bias-corrected differential measure describing the gain or loss of accessibility of a given genomic annotation relative to the average cell profile",
      "asbval:note": "Core claim is directly supported. The paper explicitly describes background peak selection matched for GC content and accessibility, and their use in computing bias-corrected deviations to remove technical confounds.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4401",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "background-peak-selection-normalization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Select GC content and accessibility-matched background peaks to normalize bias-corrected deviation scores in chromatin accessibility analysis. This normalization step removes technical artifacts and ensures that motif deviation scores reflect true biological variability rather th",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:39:29.679088+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/background-peak-selection-normalization/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "we have developed chromVAR, a versatile R package for analyzing sparse chromatin accessibility data by measuring the gain or loss of chromatin accessibility within sets of genomic features while controlling for known technical biases in epigenomic data",
      "asbval:note": "chromVAR is confirmed as the tool performing background-based normalization and deviation computation. However, the paper does not explicitly name the functions 'getBackgroundPeaks()' or 'computeDeviations()' in the provided passages. The paper describes the algorithm and workflow but does not list specific function names in the excerpts provided.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4401",
