    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/background-peak-selection-normalization/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "chromVAR first computes a \"raw accessibility deviation\" for each motif and cell, representing the difference between the total number of fragments mapping to peaks containing the given motif and the total expected number of fragments based on the average of all input cells. This aggregation across peaks sharing a common motif yields a signal that is considerably less sparse than the signal within individual peaks, however this aggregation can also amplify technical biases between cells due to PCR amplification or variable Tn5 tagmentation conditions (Supplementary Note 1). These technical biases can lead to differences in the number of observed fragment counts between cells for a given peak set with distinct GC content or mean accessibility (Supplementary Fig. 2). To account for these technical confounders, \"background\" peak sets are created for each annotation, which comprise of an equal number of peaks matched for GC content and average accessibility",
      "asbval:note": "The workflow order is clearly described: raw deviations are computed first, then background peak sets are created to correct for biases, then bias-corrected deviations and z-scores are computed.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4401",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "background-peak-selection-normalization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Background-peak-selection-normalization is used after computing expected accessibility from filtered peak and sample counts, and before computing final deviation scores",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:39:29.679088+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/background-peak-selection-normalization/008",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "All single-cell epigenomic methods are intrinsically sparse, as the total potential signal at a genomic locus is fundamentally limited by the copy number of DNA, thus generating 0, 1 or 2 reads from regulatory elements within a diploid genome. Methods developed for single cell RNA-seq have shown that measuring the dispersion of gene sets, such as Gene Ontology or co-expression modules, rather than individual genes can be a powerful approach for analyzing sparse data. In this vein, and building on previous work from our group and others, we have developed chromVAR, a versatile R package for analyzing sparse chromatin accessibility data",
      "asbval:note": "The paper explicitly addresses sparse single-cell epigenomic data as the motivation and application domain for chromVAR.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4401",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "background-peak-selection-normalization",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Background-peak normalization is designed for single-cell or sample-level sparse data",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:39:29.679088+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/benchmark-table-parsing-and-aggregation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "The paper is a methods paper introducing chromVAR, not a benchmarking study that compares multiple methods across datasets with tabulated performance matrices. While chromVAR is applied to multiple datasets and compared to PCA and peak-based approaches, the paper does not present method-by-dataset performance matrices in tabular form suitable for aggregation into TSV format. The comparisons are qualitative or embedded in figures (e.g., clustering accuracy comparisons in Supplementary Fig. 7), not structured benchmark tables.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4401",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "benchmark-table-parsing-and-aggregation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Extract method-by-dataset performance matrices from peer-reviewed benchmarking studies, compute summary statistics (mean, median, rank), and compile results into a standardized TSV format to enable quantitative comparison of competing computational methods.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:39:50.683654+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/benchmark-table-parsing-and-aggregation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": null,
      "asbval:note": "The paper does not present a benchmarking study with structured performance matrices. It is a methods paper demonstrating chromVAR's applicability across datasets (hematopoietic cells, AML, K562, GM12878, HEK293T, bulk ATAC, DNase). Comparisons to PCA and peak-based approaches are mentioned but not presented as extractable benchmark tables with numeric metrics aggregated across datasets.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-nmeth-4401",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "benchmark-table-parsing-and-aggregation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Extract method-by-dataset performance matrices from peer-reviewed benchmarking studies, compute summary statistics (mean, median, rank), and compile results into a standardized TSV format to enable quantitative comparison of competing computational methods.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0007675"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T19:39:50.683654+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000340"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/benchmark-table-parsing-and-aggregation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
